.TH PAM_LINUX_HELLO 8 "18 December 2025" "linux-hello 1.0.0" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
pam_linux_hello \- PAM module for facial authentication
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B auth    sufficient    pam_exec.so quiet stdout /usr/lib/linux-hello/pam_linux_hello.py [options]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B pam_linux_hello
is a PAM (Pluggable Authentication Module) that enables facial recognition for system
authentication. It can be used for login, sudo, and other system authentication services.
.PP
The module attempts to recognize the user's face via the Linux Hello daemon.
If successful (sufficient control flag), it allows authentication without requiring a password.
If unsuccessful, authentication falls back to the next PAM module (typically password).
.SH MODULE OPTIONS
The PAM module accepts the following options:
.TP
.B debug
Enable debug logging to system journal (verbose output)
.TP
.B timeout=SECONDS
Set timeout for face recognition (default: 5 seconds)
.TP
.B max_attempts=N
Maximum recognition attempts before failing (default: 3)
.SH CONTROL FLAGS
The module uses the `sufficient` control flag:
.TP
.B sufficient
If the module succeeds, the user is authenticated without checking further modules.
If the module fails, subsequent modules are checked (password fallback).
.PP
This is the recommended configuration for face-based authentication with password fallback.
.SH CONFIGURATION
.SS Enable for Login
Edit `/etc/pam.d/login`:
.PP
.RS
auth    sufficient    pam_exec.so quiet stdout /usr/lib/linux-hello/pam_linux_hello.py
auth    required      pam_unix.so nullok try_first_pass
.RE
.SS Enable for Sudo
Edit `/etc/pam.d/sudo`:
.PP
.RS
auth    sufficient    pam_exec.so quiet stdout /usr/lib/linux-hello/pam_linux_hello.py
auth    include       common-auth
.RE
.SS Enable for GDM/LightDM
Edit `/etc/pam.d/gdm-password` or `/etc/pam.d/lightdm`:
.PP
.RS
auth    sufficient    pam_exec.so quiet stdout /usr/lib/linux-hello/pam_linux_hello.py
auth    required      pam_unix.so try_first_pass nullok
.RE
.SH OPERATION
When invoked:
.TP
1. Module connects to Linux Hello daemon via Unix socket `/run/linux-hello.sock`
.TP
2. Passes PAM_USER (username) to the daemon
.TP
3. Daemon attempts face recognition via camera
.TP
4. Recognition result is returned (success/failure with similarity score)
.TP
5. Module passes/fails authentication accordingly
.SH RETURN VALUES
.TP
.B PAM_SUCCESS
Face recognized successfully (similarity above threshold)
.TP
.B PAM_AUTH_ERR
Face not recognized or authentication failed
.TP
.B PAM_SYSTEM_ERR
System error (socket, daemon unavailable, etc.)
.TP
.B PAM_USER_UNKNOWN
User not found in face database
.TP
.B PAM_SERVICE_ERR
Service error (timeout, camera unavailable, etc.)
.SH LOGGING
All authentication attempts are logged to systemd journal:
.PP
View PAM authentication logs:
.B journalctl -u systemd-logind -f
.PP
View PAM module logs:
.B journalctl SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER=pam_linux_hello
.PP
Enable debug logging in PAM config:
.B pam_exec.so quiet stdout /usr/lib/linux-hello/pam_linux_hello.py debug
.SH TROUBLESHOOTING
.TP
"Socket missing"
.B sudo systemctl start linux-hello
.TP
"User not found"
Register the user: `sudo hello add USERNAME`
.TP
"Camera inaccessible"
Check camera permissions: `sudo usermod -aG video $USER`
.TP
"Timeout"
Increase timeout parameter: `timeout=10`
.TP
"Face not recognized"
Re-register the user with better lighting: `sudo hello add USERNAME`
.SH SECURITY
.TP
Socket Protection
The socket `/run/linux-hello.sock` has permissions 0666 allowing any user
to attempt authentication. Only valid registered users will be recognized.
.TP
Face Database
Face embeddings are stored in `/var/lib/linux-hello/faces/` with restrictive
permissions (0700) accessible only to root.
.TP
PAM Integration
The module runs as root via `pam_exec.so`, allowing access to the daemon socket.
.TP
Fallback Mechanism
Authentication always falls back to password entry if face recognition fails,
ensuring system access even with hardware issues.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Enable for sudo with debug:
.B auth    sufficient    pam_exec.so quiet stdout /usr/lib/linux-hello/pam_linux_hello.py debug
.TP
Enable with custom timeout:
.B auth    sufficient    pam_exec.so quiet stdout /usr/lib/linux-hello/pam_linux_hello.py timeout=10
.TP
Enable with multiple attempts:
.B auth    sufficient    pam_exec.so quiet stdout /usr/lib/linux-hello/pam_linux_hello.py max_attempts=5
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /usr/lib/linux-hello/pam_linux_hello.py
The PAM module executable
.TP
.B /run/linux-hello.sock
Unix socket for daemon communication
.TP
.B /var/lib/linux-hello/faces/
Face embeddings database
.TP
.B /etc/linux-hello/config.json
System configuration
.SH DEPENDENCIES
.TP
.B linux-hello-daemon
The daemon must be running for face authentication to work
.TP
.B libpam0g
PAM library (usually pre-installed)
.TP
.B pam-exec
The `pam_exec.so` module for executing custom programs
